The Enclosure of Everything: Jeff Bezos, the Artificial General Engineer, and the Quiet End of the Knowledge Commons

In the spring of 1750, an English farmer in Northamptonshire could walk his cattle across open fields that his family had used for generations. By the spring of 1760, those fields were fenced. Parliament had passed an Enclosure Act — one of thousands — converting common land into private property without consulting the farmer or requiring his consent. When the fence went up, a way of life that had sustained communities for centuries ended not with a revolution, but with a surveyor's stake and a property deed.
The farmer could still see the land. He could still name the plants that grew there. He could still remember the path his grandfather had walked to reach the creek where the water ran clean,  but the land was no longer his. Their land now belonged to someone who had the capital to claim it and the legal standing to hold it. What the farmer lost was not merely access, but the material foundation on which his autonomy, his livelihood, and his capacity to participate in the life of his community depended.
Karl Polanyi, writing two centuries later in The Great Transformation, understood that enclosure was not simply a property transfer. It was the conversion of something that existed prior to the market — land, communal knowledge, the accumulated practices of generations — into a commodity. Polanyi called these "fictitious commodities": labor, land, and money. They were not produced for sale. They were the preconditions for economic life itself. To treat them as market goods was not merely unjust. It was structurally self-destructive. The market that consumed its own foundations could not survive on what was left.
We are living through a second enclosure. This time, the commons being fenced is not land. It is knowledge — specifically, the accumulated operational knowledge of how the physical world has been engineered, manufactured, and built over the past century. For a new entity, now seeks to create a new knowledge fence and steal the fire of the material world and their name is Jeff Bezos, the company that will make this possible, is called Prometheus. 

In November 2025, Jeff Bezos — the founder of Amazon, the owner of Blue Origin, the man who built the most consequential logistics infrastructure in human history — stepped back into an operational CEO role for the first time since leaving Amazon in 2021. His new venture, originally called Project Prometheus and since shortened to simply Prometheus, launched with $6.2 billion in initial funding and a stated mission that sounds, at first glance, almost quaint: to build better tools for engineers.
By June 2026, Prometheus had raised $18 billion, was valued at $41 billion, and had assembled a team of 150 researchers recruited from OpenAI, Google DeepMind, Meta AI, and xAI. Its investors included JPMorgan Chase, Goldman Sachs, and BlackRock. Its co-CEO, Vik Bajaj — a physicist and chemist who co-founded Alphabet's Verily and holds a PhD from MIT — described the company's ambition as making "the dream-build loop ten times faster."
Bezos himself, in one of his rare public statements about the venture, used a phrase that deserves more attention than it has received. Prometheus, he said, is building an "artificial general engineer."
The term is doing enormous rhetorical work. It deliberately echoes "artificial general intelligence" — the speculative horizon that dominates AI discourse — but redirects the concept from cognition to production. Not: can AI think like us? But: can AI build like us, faster? This distinction matters, because the second question is where the economic transformation actually lives. A machine that thinks is a philosophical problem. A machine that engineers is a labor-market event.
But Prometheus is not, at bottom, a labor-market story. It is a property story. And understanding why requires following the logic past the press releases and into the structural mechanics of what is actually being built.

Large language models — the technology behind ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, and their proliferating cousins — were made possible by a particular historical accident: the existence of the internet as a vast, publicly accessible corpus of human text. Common Crawl, the nonprofit web archive that provided the foundational training data for most major language models, contains petabytes of text scraped from billions of web pages. It is, in effect, a digital commons — the accumulated written output of humanity, sitting in the open, available to anyone with the compute and engineering talent to process it.
This is why the AI race in language models has been, despite its enormous cost, fundamentally contestable. OpenAI trained on Common Crawl. So did Meta, when it built LLaMA. So did Anthropic, and Google, and dozens of smaller competitors. The raw material was shared. The moats were in architecture, compute, talent, distribution — all real advantages, but all, in principle, replicable. Someone with sufficient resources could build a competing model because the training data was not proprietary. The internet belonged to no one, which meant it was available to everyone.
Physical AI has no equivalent commons.
The knowledge required to train an AI model that can actually engineer physical systems — that can design a jet engine, optimize a semiconductor fabrication process, predict how a drug compound will interact with biological tissue, simulate the stress tolerance of an aerospace alloy — does not exist on the internet. It exists inside companies. It is encoded in proprietary sensor data, machine logs, CAD files, simulation results, quality control records, metallurgical test outcomes, production line parameters, and the accumulated institutional memory of engineers who spent careers learning how specific materials behave under specific conditions over specific time spans.
This data is fragmented across thousands of firms. Much of it has never been digitized. What has been digitized is stored in incompatible formats, locked behind proprietary systems, and guarded — correctly — as competitive advantage. No aerospace company will voluntarily share decades of turbine performance data with a startup. No semiconductor manufacturer will open its fabrication logs to an outside AI lab. The data is the moat for those companies. Sharing it is not collaboration. It is capitulation.
Bezos understood this immediately, and through the quest to develop an AGE, has come up with a solution that is elegant in its structural ruthlessness.
If you cannot access the data through licensing, and you cannot replicate it through simulation with sufficient fidelity, then you must own the entities that generate it. Buy the companies. When you own the manufacturer, you own the data. Every sensor reading, every engineering revision, every production run outcome — it flows into your model as a structural entitlement of ownership with no negotiation, access restrictions, or competitive concern.
This is what the reported $100 billion holding company is for. It is not just another venture fund or a technology investment, but a manufacturing acquisition vehicle — designed to buy distressed or underperforming industrial companies, extract their operational data, feed it into the Prometheus model, use the improved model to optimize the acquired company's operations, and use the resulting profits to acquire the next company. A flywheel — not of users or network effects, as in the digital economy, but of data from the physical world, compounding inside a proprietary structure with each acquisition.
The logic is Amazonian in its patient, structural ambition. First, you build the infrastructure, then let others depend on it, and become indispensable, but the object of infrastructure here is not commerce or cloud computing. It is the knowledge of how things are made.

Hannah Arendt, in The Human Condition, drew a distinction that most of her readers remember and few fully absorb. She separated human activity into three categories: labor (the biological cycle of survival), work (the fabrication of the durable world of objects and institutions), and action (speech and deed in the public realm — the activity through which political life becomes possible). For Arendt, these categories were not merely descriptive. They were hierarchical in a specific sense: action — the capacity for collective deliberation, for beginning something new, for inserting oneself into the web of human relationships — was the highest expression of human freedom. It depended on the prior existence of a stable, human-built world of objects and institutions within which action could take place.
The "dream-build loop" that Bezos describes — the cycle from imagination to manufactured reality — is, in Arendt's terms, the domain of work. Work, for Arendt, was never merely technical. The act of building things involved deliberation, judgment, collective problem-solving, contestation. A jet engine is not merely the output of an engineering process, but it is the residue of thousands of decisions made by hundreds of people over years — decisions about materials, tolerances, tradeoffs, safety margins, aesthetic considerations, and the always-present question of what kind of world we are building and for whom.
What Prometheus proposes is the compression of that entire deliberative process into a computational optimization. The model designs, simulates, and decides for us. The ten-year engineering program becomes ten months, not because the model is lazy or bad at its job, to borrow Bezos's phrasing, but because it has eliminated the friction. The friction, in Arendt's framework, is the space where political subjects form. The deliberation is not an impediment to engineering. It is the process through which the people doing the engineering develop judgment, expertise, and the capacity to contest decisions they disagree with.
Remove the friction and you don't just get faster engineering, but you get a world in which the capacity to question what is being engineered — to ask why this design and not another, who benefits and who is displaced, what values are embedded in the optimization function — atrophies, and not because anyone forbids the question, but because the structure has made it unnecessary. The model already knows andl has already decided. The dream-build loop does not include a step for democratic contestation.

There is a paradox at the center of Prometheus that no one involved seems inclined to examine, though several of them are intelligent enough to see it clearly.
The promise is that the artificial general engineer will lower prices. Faster design cycles, optimized manufacturing, reduced waste, compressed production timelines — all of this translates to cheaper goods and in the standard economic narrative, cheaper goods are unambiguously good. They benefit consumers, increase access, and raise living standards.
The mechanism that produces cheaper goods is the same mechanism that eliminates the jobs that produce purchasing power. When AI automates engineering judgment — not routine assembly, not data entry, but the high-skill, high-education, high-wage work that was supposed to be automation-proof — the people displaced are not unskilled workers who can be retrained for the next rung of the ladder. They are the people who were the next rung. If the top of the skill hierarchy is vulnerable, there is no "upskill your way out" path remaining. The ladder does not have another rung to climb to.
Henry Ford understood, crudely but correctly, that production and consumption are two sides of the same circuit. He paid his workers enough to buy the cars they built — not from generosity, but from the structural recognition that a factory full of workers who cannot afford the product is a factory that has severed its own market. You cannot simultaneously eliminate the labor that produces purchasing power and expect the economy that depends on purchasing power to function. Lower prices do not help people with no income. A twenty percent reduction in the cost of a manufactured good is meaningless to someone whose job was manufacturing that good and who now earns nothing.
The standard techno-optimist response — "new jobs will emerge" — rests on a historical observation that has, until now, been roughly accurate. Agricultural workers became factory workers. Factory workers became service workers. Each transition was brutal, took generations, and involved enormous human suffering, but new categories of work eventually appeared. The economists Daron Acemoglu and Pascual Restrepo have formalized this as the tension between automation's "displacement effect" (eliminating existing tasks) and its "reinstatement effect" (creating new tasks that require human labor).
However,  there is a rate problem – When the cycle from displacement to reinstatement took decades, societies could adapt — painfully, unevenly, with immense cost, but they adapted. When AI compresses that cycle to years or months — when the same system that eliminated one category of work is already being trained on the data that will let it perform whatever new tasks emerge — the reinstatement cannot keep pace. The new jobs do not materialize fast enough, because the system that eliminated the old ones is already capable of doing the new ones.
So the price reduction is not benevolence, but structural necessity, when you have eliminated the purchasing power of the workforce, then the only way to maintain any market at all is to lower prices far enough that whatever residual income people retain — from gig work, from government transfers, from the informal economy — can still purchase something, but that is a deflationary spiral, not an economic strategy. It concentrates the remaining economic activity through the entity that controls the optimization.

Universal basic income enters the conversation here, as it always does, wearing the face of humane pragmatism. The argument sounds reasonable: tax the productivity gains from automation, distribute the proceeds as a basic income, and free people to pursue creative and meaningful work that the market does not reward. It sounds like the solution was waiting in a drawer, ready to be deployed once the automation arrived, but the math does not close. 
The tax base that funds UBI is wage income and corporate profits. If automation suppresses wages across the board, and corporate profits concentrate in a small number of AI-infrastructure companies that are expert at tax optimization — and Jeff Bezos has demonstrated considerable expertise in that domain — the revenue base for universal income shrinks precisely when the need for it expands. You cannot fund universal income from an economy that has eliminated the conditions for universal employment. The fiscal architecture collapses under its own logic and this all  assumes a political system willing to implement UBI at all — which requires a functioning democracy, which requires an engaged citizenry, which requires people with enough economic security and political agency to demand structural change. Each of those preconditions is eroded by the very process that makes UBI necessary. 
The question everyone should be asking — and almost no one is — is not whether Prometheus will work. It is what happens if it does?
Not: will the artificial general engineer successfully compress the dream-build loop? But: what happens to the human capacity for engineering judgment, for collective deliberation about what should be built and why, for the slow accumulation of knowledge through practice and error and argument — when all of that is encoded in a proprietary model owned by one entity and optimized for speed?
Not: will Prometheus's holding company successfully acquire legacy manufacturers? But: what happens to the knowledge commons of physical engineering — the informal, distributed, collectively generated understanding of how things work that has circulated for decades through industry conferences, published research, workforce mobility, shared supply chains, and the embodied expertise of working engineers — when it is enclosed inside a private structure and converted into training data for a model that no one outside the structure can access?
Not: will antitrust regulators intervene? But: what legal vocabulary, what regulatory framework, what institutional mechanism exists to address a form of consolidation that does not raise consumer prices, does not reduce product quality, does not operate through market-share dominance in any sector regulators currently monitor — but that privatizes the epistemological foundations of the physical economy? Current antitrust law asks whether consolidation harms consumers through higher prices. Prometheus will lower prices. The harm is elsewhere — in the elimination of the conditions under which competition itself is possible — and the law does not have a word for it.
Not: will someone else do it if Bezos doesn't? But: does the inevitability of a structural transformation excuse the failure to think about its consequences? The people building Prometheus are not unsophisticated. They know the history of industrialization. They know about the Engels Pause — the decades of stagnant wages and expanding poverty that followed the introduction of factory machinery, before productivity gains eventually translated into rising living standards. They know the pattern. But knowing the pattern and being structurally positioned to do anything about it are different things. Bezos is building Prometheus inside a system that will not let him build it slowly, partially, and will not let him stop, because if he stops, the position goes to someone else — and he is probably correct that the someone else may be worse.
This is the structural tragedy of it. Not Greek tragedy — no hubris, no divine punishment, no catharsis. Structural tragedy, where every actor sees the problem, every actor is constrained by the architecture they operate within and the architecture itself is what needs to change, but cannot, because changing it requires the kind of collective deliberation and long-term planning that the architecture has already made impossible.

There is a scene in Fritz Lang's Metropolis — the 1927 film that remains, nearly a century later, the most prescient meditation on the relationship between technology, labor, and power — in which the workers who operate the machines that sustain the city above them are shown moving in synchronized, mechanical patterns. They have become extensions of the apparatus they serve. Their bodies have adapted to the rhythm of the machine. Their autonomy has not been taken from them by force. It has been absorbed into the operational logic of the system, so gradually and so completely that the question of whether they are free has become structurally unanswerable.
Maria — the human woman, not the robot built in her image — tells the workers that the mediator between the head and the hands must be the heart. It is the moral thesis of the film, and it is exactly the kind of claim that the logic of Prometheus renders inoperative. The artificial general engineer does not need a heart or mediator. It compresses the head and the hands into a single optimization function and eliminates the space where the heart — where deliberation, judgment, solidarity, the capacity to ask should we build this? rather than can we build it faster? — might have intervened.
Arendt would have recognized this immediately. She called it the banality of evil — not the dramatic villainy of ideology, but the quiet abdication of judgment by people who are simply doing their jobs within a system that does not ask them to think about consequences. The banality of optimization is its contemporary form: no one intends the catastrophe, everyone contributes to it, and the catastrophe arrives not as a dramatic rupture but as the quiet completion of a logic that was visible from the start to anyone who bothered to look.

In the English enclosures, the farmers who lost access to the commons did not disappear. They became wage laborers — dependent on the owners of the enclosed land for the work that had previously been self-sustaining. The enclosure did not eliminate their capacity for labor. It eliminated their autonomy — their ability to sustain themselves outside the market, to withdraw from employment that degraded them, to say no from a position of material independence.
Polanyi understood that this was not merely an economic transformation, but also a political one. People who depend entirely on wages for survival cannot afford to resist the conditions under which those wages are offered. The enclosure of the commons was, simultaneously, the enclosure of political agency. The freedom to dissent requires a material foundation — something to fall back on and to sustain yourself outside the system you are contesting. If you remove that foundation, then dissent becomes a luxury that only the already-secure can afford.
The enclosure of engineering knowledge follows the same structural logic. When the accumulated knowledge of how to design and build physical systems is locked inside a proprietary model, the engineers who generated that knowledge lose their autonomy in a specific and devastating way. Their expertise — the thing that gave them bargaining power, professional identity, and the capacity to say this design is wrong, this tradeoff is unacceptable, this optimization is serving the wrong values — becomes redundant in the sense that the model already contains what they know and the model does not argue, demand wages, organize or ask uncomfortable questions about who benefits from the compression of the dream-build loop.
The word for a system that eliminates the material conditions under which its own correction is possible is not "innovation." It is not "progress." It is not even "monopoly," which implies a market that still exists and could, in principle, be contested.
The word is enclosure, and by the time people understand what has been enclosed, the fences are already up.

Prometheus launched from San Francisco, with offices in London and Zurich. It has no public website. It has not released a product. It has not demonstrated a capability. It has raised $18 billion on the strength of an idea — that AI can do for physical engineering what it has done for text generation — and the credibility of the man proposing it.
Whether the idea works is, in some sense, the least important question. If it works, the consequences are structural and potentially irreversible. If it doesn't work — if the artificial general engineer proves more difficult to build than Bezos and Bajaj believe — the $18 billion represents one of the most expensive failed experiments in the history of technology, but the capital will be recycled, the researchers will scatter to other ventures, and the underlying dynamic — the drive to enclose the knowledge commons of physical engineering — will continue under different names, at different companies, with different investors.
The question is not whether this particular venture succeeds. The question is whether we have any institutional capacity to think about what success would mean — not for shareholders, not for national competitiveness, not for consumer prices, but for the human beings whose knowledge, labor, and capacity for self-governance are the raw material being enclosed.
The answer to that question, if we are honest, is that we do not and not because no one is thinking about it, but because the people doing the thinking are outside the structure that has the power to act and the people inside the structure are constrained by an architecture that makes long-term thinking a competitive liability.
That gap — between the capacity to see and the capacity to act — is not a policy problem. It is a political crisis and it will not be resolved by better regulation, technology, or intentions. It will be resolved, if it is resolved at all, by the same thing that has always resolved the tension between enclosure and the commons: people who refuse to accept that the way things are is the way things must be. People who insist, against the structural logic of the system, that the knowledge of how to build the world is not a commodity to be owned but a commons to be sustained. People who understand that wonder — the capacity to look at the physical world and ask how does this work, and who does it serve, and could it be otherwise? — is not a sentimental luxury but the precondition for every form of freedom that matters.
The fences are going to go up, but the question is whether anyone is paying attention and whether that attention, at this late hour, is still enough.

C. M. Raynor is writing The Age of AI: Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Happiness After AI - A book about life after AI and the impact on technology in a modern era. 

